**Real-World Scenario:**

Consider an application that needs to fetch data from multiple API endpoints.  If one of those APIs is known to be unreliable or slow, `Promise.race()` can provide a timeout mechanism.  Instead of waiting for all APIs to complete (as `Promise.all()` would), we can use `Promise.race()` with a timeout promise. If the first API doesn't respond within a defined timeframe, `Promise.race()` will abandon it and return the result from any other API that completes first.  This prevents the application from being blocked indefinitely by a slow or unresponsive service and provides a responsive user experience.



